ng waters falling down clean and bright rocks at the Marmala Waterfalls is truly mesmerizing, best seasons to visit the waterfalls are spring and summer when the water is warm enough for a bath. Visitors should stay away during the rainy season since trekking and mountaineering may be difficult due to lightning and thunderstorms. Marmala Road in Vellani Erattupetta, Kerala, is the destination. Opening times are every week from 6 am to 6 pm. 2. Taj Juma Masjid: On the banks of the Meenachil river sits this 1,000-Year-old mosque, which claims to be the oldest mosque in Kerala. The mosque is renowned for its countless examples of historical and cultural elegance. It has become a popular destination for visitors and relaxation lovers due to the beauty of its architectural design, beautiful woodwork, and lush green surroundings. The mosque's natural beauty is extremely outstanding and is similar to that of a palace. The traditional Indo-Russian influence of the fresco painting at the mosque will also be available for tourists to enjoy. Its serene and spiritual atmosphere makes for a wonderful vacation. Tourist Bangalow Road, across from Joy Alukkas, is where you'll find Eerayii Kadavu in Kottayam, Kerala. Opening times are Every day of the week, from 6 am until 8 3. Kumarakom Bird Sanctuary: The Kumarakom bird sanctuary, gorgeously situated by the Vembanad Lake's shores, is home to a wide variety of rare, colourful, and beautiful bird species. Visitors may relax on the 14-acre area of lush, beautiful green meadows and enjoy the colourful birds in flight. This paradise for birdwatchers displays its various avifauna species and attracts wildlife enthusiasts from all over the world. Couples on their honeymoon, those who like picnics, and tourists and visitors looking for a quiet place to rest and relax may find joy at the sanctuary. Kavanattinkara, Kumarakom, Kerala, is the location. Opening times are Every day of the week, 6 am to 5 pm. Before entering the sanctuary, visitors must purchase tickets from the official counter (INR 50 for Indians and INR 100 for non-Indians). 4. Mozart Art Gallery: Art lovers and fans should attend this well-kept private art gallery in Aymanam as a getaway. This gallery offers a platform for artists from all regions of the world to view examples of modern and vintage paintings, drawings, and other works of art and learn about the processes and techniques used in painting and sketching. The display of unique mythological and religious drawings from Kerala, antiques, and other cultural-historical objects adds to the splendour of this museum. Visitors might also stroll around the Aymanam village's natural surroundings and peaceful backwaters. 3442, Kallum Kathara Road, Aymanam, Kottayam, Kerala. Opening times are 9:30 am to 5:30 pm, seven days a week. 5. Elaveezha Poonchira: Do you want to go on a hiking or trekking excursion where you may enjoy the attraction of the floral scent? Then you have to go to the ElaveezhaPoonchira. This valley, situated between three majestic hillocks, provides an incredible view of the city from its apex. Additionally, it provides a breathtakingly lovely and stunning view of the sunset. Picnic lovers would undoubtedly find a trip to this location worthwhile with the waterfalls. Melukavu village in Kottayam, Kerala, is the location. Visitors should stay away during the rainy season since trekking and mountaineering may be difficult due to lightning and thunderstorms. 6. Mary Orthodox Church: This 440-year-old church, also known as Kottayam Cheriapali, is in the centre of Kottayam city. Devotees and pilgrims would be fascinated by the church's combination of Kerala and Portuguese architectural styles, its excellent architectural framework, delightful paintings, and lovely murals. The European architectural style has long been a tourist attraction since it is adorned with pillars, pediments, cornices, and galleries. The church's murals show biblical and non-biblical topics and Western and Oriental styles. On January 15th, the church has a yearly celebration as well. Tourists and devotees from around the world gather on the church grounds to observe the celebrations during this feast. You will be in wonder at the church's beautiful surroundings, spiritual aura, and emotional drawing exhibit. The location is Oppotil Junction on the Kumarakom Road in Kottayam, Kerala. Opening times are every day of the week from 8 am to 6 pm. 7. Monroe Lighthouse: The Monroe Lighthouse has established itself as a major tourist destination in Kottayam, surrounded by attractive waterways, islands, and lakes. Tourists may enjoy the splendour of viewing the Vembanad lake, experiencing the romance of sunset and sunrise, and observing unique bird species flying from this vantage point that provides a panoramic view of the town. Tourists should be prepared to participate in fishing activities and enjoyable boat races, given the areas near the Vembanad lake. Location: Kerala's Collectorate of Kottayam, Kumily Opening times are every day of the week from 10 am to 8 pm. 8. Vaikom: Tourists wishing to escape the rush of city life will find Viacom an outstanding destination. It is cool, peaceful, and lonely. Its near to prominent temples, historical attractions, and Kerala's beautiful backwaters add to its attraction. Visitors may have a luxurious stay because there are so many affordable hotels and resorts. Kottayam district in Kerala is the location. 9. Bay Island Driftwood Museum: This well-known museum in Kumarakom offers a large collection of fine driftwood items with exceptional aesthetic value created using a unique and creative modern art technique. The museum's varied collections of root sculptures come in various forms, themes, patterns, and designs, which will delight visitors. The owner, passionate about antiquities and has accumulated them throughout her life, runs and oversees this excellent museum. Tourists who appreciate the arts shouldn't pass up a trip to this museum since, according to rumours, the curator and owner's excitement and passion are generally passed on to her tourists. Chakranpadi, Vayitharamattom, Kumarakom, and Kottayam are the locations in Opening times are every day of the week from 10 am to 5 pm. 10. Illikkal Kallu: The sunrise and sunset views from one of Kottayam's highest peaks are beautiful. This natural peak's peacefulness and peaceful aura, which represents the pure beauty of Rocky Mountains, is calming and energizing. One may argue that the top is gifted with great natural happiness because of its lovely atmosphere and hills covered in lush greenery. At this paradisiacal mountain, hiking, trekking, and picnics become common activities. Would you want to take a holiday in a faraway place? The Illikkal Kallu should therefore be included in your journey. Location: Erattupetta, Moonnilavu, Illikkal Kallu Road, Kottayam, Kerala. Opening times are Every day of the week from 8 am to 5:30 pm. 11. Nadukani: Nadukani, surrounded by heavily forested hills, provides its tourists with the best in natural beauty. Nadukani offers tourists a breathtaking view of the Nilgiri Mountains, the growing greenery on the northern side, and the sparkling waters of the Muvattupuzha river. It is elevated by a height of 3000ft above sea level and wonderfully placed on a hilltop. Tourists wouldn't want to miss the location's magical atmosphere that occurs when the fog and clouds arrive. Due to its beautiful and peaceful beauty, Nadukani has recently emerged as one of the greatest tourist destinations in Kottayam for couples seeking a sanctuary, honeymooners, and picnickers. Kottayam district in Kerala is the location. 12. Nattakom And Panachikkad: Nattakom and Panachikkad, two independent villages located a few kilometres from the city, are well recognized for their serenity and peacefulness. Despite being exclusive and lonely, these settlements provide views of unique migrating birds, stunning reservoirs, and beautiful 